My love for development stems from a love of problem solving. I enjoy true crime, mysteries, puzzles, riddles - anything that I can mull on throughout the day. An instructor actually once described my debugging style as “being a detective on the case,” and that was before they knew about all the true crime podcasts. 

The ability to have a fulfilling career that affords me the opportunity to use my professional skills for meaningful side projects motivated me to finally take the plunge and work towards becoming a developer. My ability to sew a garment or design an accessory doesn’t translate all that well to doing community work or spreading equity whereas the ability to create a small but useful app for a volunteer group or to bring inclusive ideals to pre-existing services is an actually achievable way to uplift others.

When I'm not programming, you can find me baking or working my way (slowly but determinedly) through translated Japanese pattern-making books.
